{{Infobox book <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = A Hebrew and English Lexicon of the Old Testament | title_orig = | translator = | image = [[File:A Hebrew and English Lexicon (Brown-Driver-Briggs).djvu|200px|page=7]] | caption = Impression of 1939 | author = [[Francis Brown (theologian)|Francis Brown]], [[Samuel Rolles Driver]], [[Charles Augustus Briggs]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[England]] | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | subject = [[Biblical Hebrew]] | genre = [[Reference work|Reference]] | publisher = | pub_date = 1906 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 1185 | isbn = 1-56563-206-0 | oclc = 13518063 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = A Hebrew and English Lexicon (Brown-Driver-Briggs) }} '''''A Hebrew and English Lexicon of the Old Testament''''', more commonly known as '''''Brown–Driver–Briggs''''' or '''''BDB''''' (from the name of its three authors) is a standard reference for [[Biblical Hebrew]] and [[Biblical Aramaic|Aramaic]],<ref name=BHAL2013/> first published in 1906. It is organized by (Hebrew) alphabetical order of [[triliteral|three letter roots]]. It was based on the Hebrew-German [[lexicon]] of [[Wilhelm Gesenius]], translated by [[Edward Robinson (scholar)|Edward Robinson]]. The chief editor was [[Francis Brown (theologian)|Francis Brown]], with the co-operation of [[Samuel Rolles Driver]] and [[Charles Augustus Briggs]], hence the name Brown–Driver–Briggs. Some modern printings have added the [[Strong's concordance|Strong's reference numbers]] for Biblical Hebrew and Aramaic words.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}
In 2013, [[Semitic studies|semitists]] [[Jo Ann Hackett]] and John Huehnergard received a [[National Endowment for the Humanities]] grant to fund creation of a revised and updated electronic version of the BDB; the resulting ''Biblical Hebrew and Aramaic Lexicon'' will be available through a website (''Semitica Electronica'') or via print-on-demand.<ref name=BHAL2013>{{cite web |date=11 July 2013 |title=Jo Ann Hackett and John Huehnergard Receive NEH Grant for Biblical Hebrew and Aramaic Lexicon |website=UT College of Liberal Arts |publisher=University of Texas at Austin |url=http://liberalarts.utexas.edu/mes/news/article.php?id=6768 }}</ref>
